                    <!-- End: Article Head -->

                    <!--Start: Left Rail -->

    <div id="leftRail" class="fleft clearfix article">


		<div class="body contains_vestpocket">


	        
<div class="zemanta-img"> 
 <div class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 260px">
  <a href="http://www.crunchbase.com/product/iphone"><img class="zemanta-img-configured" title="Image representing iPhone as depicted in Crunc..." src="http://b-i.forbesimg.com/janetnovack/files/2013/09/19797v1-max-250x25030.jpg" alt="Image representing iPhone as depicted in Crunc..." width="250" height="195" /></a>
  <p class="wp-caption-text">Image via CrunchBase</p>
 </div> 
</div> 
<p>In a new twist on identify theft fraud, a Michigan operation allegedly used “credit mules” posing as new or existing cell contract customers to scam thousands of free or subsidized phones from <a href="/companies/att/">AT&amp;T</a> <span class="quotecard_hook" data-ticker="T" data-exchange="NYSE" data-type="organization" data-naturalid="fred/company/354" data-quotes-closing="34.05" data-quotes-now="34.23"><span class="wrapper"><a href="/companies/att/">AT&amp;T</a></span></span>, Verizon Wireless, &nbsp;<a href="/companies/best-buy/">Best Buy</a> <span class="quotecard_hook" data-ticker="BBY" data-exchange="NYSE" data-type="organization" data-naturalid="fred/company/597" data-quotes-closing="38.0" data-quotes-now="38.53"><span class="wrapper"><a href="/companies/best-buy/">Best Buy</a></span></span>, Radio Shack and <a href="/companies/apple/">Apple</a> <span class="quotecard_hook" data-ticker="AAPL" data-exchange="NASDAQ" data-type="organization" data-naturalid="fred/company/280" data-quotes-closing="481.6001" data-quotes-now="486.28"><span class="wrapper"><a href="/companies/apple/">Apple</a></span></span>&nbsp;stores. &nbsp;According to a previously unreported federal lawsuit filed last Friday, during a four month investigation, U.S. Secret Service agents watched as individuals carrying Apple iPhone boxes and cell store shopping bags trooped into a store in Taylor, Michigan run by iBuy Express, Inc.,&nbsp; dealt with a clerk shielded by bullet proof glass, and then left iBuy without their boxes and bags, but with wads of cash. Investigators riffling through iBuy’s trash found bags from AT&amp;T, Verizon Wireless, Best Buy, Radio Shack and Apple stores; receipts for phones shipped by AT&amp;T and Verizon to Michigan addresses; and SIM cards, indicating, the government alleges, that the phones were being unlocked or hacked for sale in overseas markets.</p> 
<p>According to the suit, the credit mules sometimes scammed new, subsidized phones by using stolen identities to sign new two year cell phone service contracts with multiple carriers. At other times they used “account takeovers”— posing as an established customer who wants to add new &nbsp;lines and phones to his or her cell plan. (Account takeovers are facilitated by the fact that account<a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/janetnovack/2010/11/23/how-i-failed-my-bank-security-test-and-a-thief-might-pass/">&nbsp;security questions are often drawn from public records</a> and credit reports relating to the account holder.) Sometimes, “recruiters” would find individuals ready to be mules and drive them from store to store, the suit says.</p> 
<p>Backing up the overseas connection, during its investigation, the government intercepted <a href="/companies/fedex/">FedEx</a> <span class="quotecard_hook" data-ticker="FDX" data-exchange="NYSE" data-type="organization" data-naturalid="fred/company/1564" data-quotes-closing="113.57" data-quotes-now="113.56"><span class="wrapper"><a href="/companies/fedex/">FedEx</a></span></span> packages being shipped from an iBuy warehouse to Hong Kong and Dubai—packages which contained 299 cell phones, including 255 that Verizon and AT&amp;T later identified as having been obtained through suspected identity fraud, contract fraud and theft, the lawsuit says. Finally, in April, the Secret Service moved in, seizing &nbsp;more than $800,000 and 5,300 phones (including more than 500 iPhone 5 and iPhone 4S handsets) from three locations and from a bank account associated with iBuy. &nbsp;The suit,&nbsp; filed last week by the U.S. Attorney for the Eastern District of Michigan–technically a “Complaint for Forfeiture” –seeks to keep the haul on the grounds that the cash and phones result from violations of federal identity theft and mail and wire fraud laws, as well as the interstate transport of stolen merchandise and money laundering.&nbsp;A spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorney said there are no criminal charges currently pending associated with the iBuy forfeiture, but declined to say whether a criminal investigation is ongoing.</p> 
<p>As an indication of just how big the operation had gotten, the government says that between Jan. 2 and March 12<sup>th</sup> of this year, iBuy’s account at Citizen’s Bank of Michigan posted $6.9 million of wire transfers in and $3.3 million in transfers out and that an armored car service was used to deliver cash from the account to iBuy’s storefront.</p> 
<p>The main number for iBuy is no longer in service. An attorney who represented iBuy in an earlier civil case did not return a call for comment. In that case, Sprint Corp. alleged iBuy Express had infringed on its business and stolen its “subsidy investment” by encouraging “runners” to make bulk purchases of the Sprint iPhone 4S and other Sprint contract phones and then hacking and reselling the phones, often overseas. The suit alleged iBuy and its mules &nbsp;compounded their profits by purchasing insurance for the phones and then reporting them lost, stolen or damaged and receiving replacement phones, which were also peddled overseas. A district judge entered a final order in that case in June 2012, &nbsp;awarding Sprint $2 million in damages and permanently barring iBuy and its officers from buying, selling or unlocking Sprint phones.</p> 
<p><em><a href="http://www.twitter.com/janetnovack">Follow Janet Novack on Twitter</a></em></p> 
